\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/lfunction.dirichlet}{Dirichlet L-function}}
\begin{definition*}\label{lfunction.dirichlet}
\uses{character.dirichlet,character.dirichlet.conductor,lfunction,lfunction.dirichlet_series,lfunction.euler_product,lfunction.functional_equation}
A \textbf{Dirichlet L-function} is an \hyperref[lfunction]{L-function} defined by a \hyperref[lfunction.dirichlet_series]{Dirichlet series} of the form ${\displaystyle L(s, \chi)=\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac {\chi(n)}{n^s}}$, where $\chi$ is a \hyperref[character.dirichlet]{Dirichlet character}.  

Dirichlet L-functions can be meromorphically continued to the complex plane, have an \hyperref[lfunction.euler_product]{Euler product} ${\displaystyle L(s, \chi)= \prod_p (1 - \chi(p) p^{-s} )^{-1}}$, and satisfy a \hyperref[lfunction.functional_equation]{functional equation} of the form
\[
\Lambda(s,\chi) = q^{s/2} \Gamma_{\mathbb R} (s) L(s,\chi) = \varepsilon_\chi \overline{\Lambda}(1-s),
\]
where $q$ is the \hyperref[character.dirichlet.conductor]{conductor} of $\chi$.

These L-functions were introduced by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter\_Gustav\_Lejeune\_Dirichlet">Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet</a> in the mid-1800s as a tool to study prime numbers in arithmetic progressions.  
\end{definition*}


